    name: "Tharu Cultural Village",
    category: "CULTURAL_VILLAGE",
    summary: "The Tharu are the indigenous people of Nepal's Terai, renowned for their genetic resistance to malaria and their centuries-old forest-dwelling culture. Villages near Sauraha in Chitwan offer visitors an authentic window into Tharu life through traditional mud-and-bamboo architecture, artisan craft workshops, and the electrifying Tharu stick dance performed every evening. Guided village walks, ox-cart tours, and homestays provide genuine cultural exchange beyond the national park experience.",
    story: `<p>The Tharu people have inhabited the malaria-prone Terai forests of Nepal for well over a thousand years, developing a remarkable biological immunity to the disease that kept outsiders at bay until the 1950s. In Chitwan, Tharu villages cluster along the buffer zone of the national park, particularly around Sauraha and Bagmara. Traditional homesteads are built of mud, clay, and bamboo with thatched roofs, the exterior walls decorated with intricate geometric murals painted by women using natural earth pigments. Entire extended families live in long communal structures that face an inner courtyard—a spatial arrangement that reflects the tight-knit social fabric of Tharu society.</p><p>The village walk is the centrepiece of the cultural experience. Accompanied by a Tharu guide, visitors thread through rice paddies and mustard fields to reach working homesteads where potters throw clay on hand-turned wheels, weavers work wooden looms producing the distinctive Tharu dhurrie rugs, and women pound rice with long wooden pestles in a rhythmic communal exercise. Fish traps woven from bamboo strips hang drying in doorways—fishing in the Rapti's backwaters supplements the rice and lentil diet that defines Tharu cuisine. The guide explains animist rituals, the role of the shaman (guruwa), and how Tharu festivals like Maghi (New Year in January) and Chitwan's Tharu culture festival mark the agricultural calendar.</p><p>Every evening in Sauraha, cultural troupes perform the Tharu stick dance (Danda Nach) and Peacock Dance to the beat of the madal drum and the haunting notes of the bansuri flute. Male dancers manipulate pairs of hardwood sticks with extraordinary precision, clashing them together in complex patterns that mimic both martial combat and ceremonial ritual. For a deeper engagement, several community lodges around Bachhauli and Kumroj offer homestays where guests share meals, join the family's morning rice harvest, and learn to weave a basic dhurrie—income that flows directly to the host family rather than to tour intermediaries.</p><ul><li>Indigenous community with centuries-old cultural traditions and malaria-resistant genetics</li><li>Traditional mud-and-bamboo homes with intricate geometric murals painted by women</li><li>Guided village walks through rice fields, pottery workshops, and weaving demonstrations</li><li>Evening Tharu stick dance (Danda Nach) and Peacock Dance performances in Sauraha</li><li>Ox-cart village tours and bicycle rides through surrounding farmland</li><li>Homestays with local families at Bachhauli and Kumroj community lodges</li></ul>`,
