    name: "Devghat Dham",
    category: "TEMPLE",
    summary: "Devghat is one of Nepal's holiest Hindu pilgrimage sites, located at the sacred confluence of the Trishuli and Kali Gandaki rivers\u2014together forming the mighty Narayani\u2014about 7 km northwest of Narayanghat. Ashrams, temples, and cave shrines line the wooded riverbanks, sheltering hundreds of sadhus and elderly devotees who come to spend their final years at this spiritually charged tirtha. During the Makar Sankranti festival in January, hundreds of thousands of pilgrims descend for ritual bathing in one of Nepal's largest religious gatherings.",
    story: `<p>Devghat occupies the triangular wedge of land where the Trishuli River—sweeping south from the mountains above Kathmandu—merges with the Kali Gandaki, which has carved the world's deepest gorge on its journey from the Mustang plateau. The combined stream, now called the Narayani, is sacred to Hindus as a manifestation of Vishnu himself, and the Shaligram stones—ammonite fossils found in the riverbed—are venerated as the direct embodiment of the deity. Mention of Devghat appears in the Baraha Purana, Skanda Purana, and Padma Purana, underscoring its antiquity as a pilgrimage destination. The site lies on the boundary of Tanahun, Chitwan, and Nawalpur districts in Gandaki Province, a geographical convergence that mirrors its spiritual significance as a meeting point of sacred waters.</p><p>Walking through Devghat's forest paths feels like entering a living monastery. Dozens of ashrams—many founded centuries ago—provide food and lodging to wandering sadhus and to the community of retired Hindus who have chosen to spend their final years here in the belief that dying at this tirtha ensures moksha (liberation from the cycle of rebirth). Smoke from dhuni fires mingles with the scent of marigold garlands and incense at shrines to Shiva, Vishnu, Hanuman, and a cave temple associated with Goddess Sita. Small stone ghats step down to the river where pilgrims perform tarpan rituals for deceased ancestors, pouring water cupped in their palms back into the confluence.</p><p>Makar Sankranti—falling in mid-January when the sun transitions into Capricorn—transforms Devghat into one of Nepal's largest festivals. Hundreds of thousands of pilgrims arrive by bus, jeep, and on foot, bathing in the confluence before dawn to wash away sins accumulated over the year. Tent cities spring up along the riverbanks, and the chanting of Vedic hymns continues through the night. Outside festival time, Devghat rewards the unhurried traveller with its peaceful atmosphere, forest walks, and extraordinary bird life along the river—bee-eaters, kingfishers, and osprey are commonly seen. The site is 20 km from Sauraha and makes an excellent half-day cultural excursion from a Chitwan base.</p><ul><li>Sacred confluence of Trishuli and Kali Gandaki rivers, forming the Narayani</li><li>Mentioned in the Baraha Purana, Skanda Purana, and Padma Purana</li><li>Hundreds of ashrams, sadhus, and elderly devotees in permanent residence</li><li>Makar Sankranti festival (mid-January) draws hundreds of thousands of pilgrims</li><li>Shaligram stones (ammonite fossils) venerated as manifestations of Vishnu</li><li>Cave shrine associated with Goddess Sita; multiple temples along the ghats</li></ul>`,
