    name: "World Peace Pagoda",
    category: "STUPA",
    summary: "Pokhara's World Peace Pagoda (Shanti Stupa) crowns Ananda Hill at 1,100 metres above Phewa Lake, offering a 360-degree panorama of the Annapurna and Dhaulagiri ranges alongside a bird's-eye view of the lake and the Pokhara Valley. Built by Japanese Buddhist monks of the Nipponzan-My\u014dh\u014dji order and inaugurated in 1999, the gleaming white stupa enshrines relics of the Buddha beneath its central chamber. A steep 45-minute hike through forest from the lakeside, or a short boat-and-hike combination, rewards visitors with one of the finest vantage points in Nepal.",
    story: `<p>The World Peace Pagoda on Pokhara's southern hillside is one of 80 peace pagodas built worldwide by the Nipponzan-Myōhōji Buddhist order under the guidance of Japanese monk Nichidatsu Fujii, who laid the foundation stone—along with relics of the Gautama Buddha—on 12 September 1973. Construction took over two decades of local volunteer labour and Japanese donations, with the inaugural ceremony conducted on 30 October 1999 in the presence of former Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala. The pagoda stands 35 metres tall (115 feet) and is 105 metres wide (344 feet), its two tiers clad in brilliant white plaster and adorned with four gilded Buddha figures facing the cardinal directions, each depicting a different episode in the Buddha's life: birth, enlightenment, preaching, and nirvana.</p><p>Reaching the pagoda is itself a rewarding journey. The forest trail ascends steeply from the Lakeside boat landing at Damside, winding through a subtropical forest of oak, rhododendron, and pine that shelters langur monkeys and an impressive variety of forest birds including the scarlet minivet, great barbet, and Asian paradise flycatcher. The hike takes approximately 45 minutes at a steady pace and gains about 350 metres of elevation. Alternatively, visitors can take a rowing boat south across the lake from the main Lakeside ghats to the Phewa Lake boat landing near Anada Hill, then hike 30 minutes through the forest directly to the pagoda—a route that avoids road-side noise and is highly recommended at dawn.</p><p>From the pagoda's upper terrace, the panorama is transformative. Phewa Lake glitters 350 metres below, its surface dotted with rowing boats and edged by the hotel strip and forest. The Annapurna South (7,219 m), Hiunchuli (6,441 m), and Machapuchare (6,993 m) rise immediately to the north, while Dhaulagiri (8,167 m) anchors the western horizon and the long ridgeline of the Annapurna II, III, and IV group extends east. On winter mornings, cloud inversions fill the lower valleys while the peaks stand clear above in alpenglow—a sight that has made this viewpoint one of the most photographed spots in all of Nepal. The pagoda's resident monk rings the bell at intervals throughout the day, its deep resonance rolling across the lake and valley below.</p><ul><li>Built by Japanese Nipponzan-Myōhōji monks; inaugurated 1999; enshrines Buddha relics</li><li>Elevation 1,100 m; 35 m tall; two-tiered white pagoda with four gilded Buddhas</li><li>360-degree panorama: Phewa Lake below, Annapurna and Dhaulagiri ranges above</li><li>45-minute forest hike from Damside, or boat+hike combination from Lakeside</li><li>Best light for photography at sunrise and late afternoon</li><li>Free entry; resident monks present for prayer and meditation</li></ul>`,
