    category: "MONASTERY",
    summary: "Matepani Gumba is a serene Tibetan Buddhist monastery perched on a small wooded hill five kilometres east of central Pokhara, established in 1960 by Nyeshang families who migrated from the Manang valley following Tibetan refugees into Nepal. The monastery's main hall houses large statues of Shakyamuni Buddha, Padmasambhava, and Karmapa, their gilded surfaces gleaming in the lamplight, and the walls are covered with detailed thangka paintings of the Buddhist cosmology. From the hilltop, panoramic views extend across Pokhara to Machapuchare and the full Annapurna range.",
    story: `<p>Matepani Gumba stands in the Kundahar district of Pokhara at coordinates 28.2165°N, 84.0074°E, on a green hillock east of the city that has been a site of Buddhist practice since the monastery's founding in 1960 A.D. The founding community consisted of Nyeshang people from the high-altitude Manang valley—traders and farmers who had centuries of involvement with Tibetan Buddhist culture through the trans-Himalayan salt and wool trade. When Tibetan refugees fled across the mountains following the 1959 Lhasa uprising, the Nyeshang diaspora in Pokhara created Matepani as a spiritual anchor for the displaced community, establishing a pattern of monastic patronage that has continued for sixty-five years. The monastery belongs to the Kagyu school of Tibetan Buddhism, the tradition most associated with the Karmapa lineage holders.</p><p>The monastery complex is entered through a traditional Tibetan gateway painted with the Eight Auspicious Symbols and flanked by white chorten (stupas). The main prayer hall—rebuilt and expanded in the 1990s—is dominated by three seated statues approximately 3.5 metres tall: Shakyamuni Buddha in the centre, Padmasambhava (the 8th-century tantric master who brought Buddhism to Tibet) on the left, and the 16th Karmapa on the right. The walls are covered floor to ceiling with thangka paintings depicting the Wheel of Life, the paradise of Amitabha, and elaborate mandala compositions. Butter lamps burn before the altar throughout the day, and the fragrance of juniper incense drifts through the hall. Approximately 50 monks reside at the monastery, following a strict daily schedule of dawn prayers, individual study, group recitation, and evening prayers.</p><p>The hilltop grounds of Matepani offer one of the finest accessible vantage points in Pokhara for mountain views without a long hike. Machapuchare (6,993 m) rises directly north in a near-perfect triangular profile, flanked by Annapurna South (7,219 m) and Hiunchuli (6,441 m). The Pokhara Valley spreads below, its lakes gleaming silver in the early morning and the city's temples and stupa visible among the trees. The monastery welcomes respectful visitors throughout the day; donations to the gompa fund go toward education and maintenance of the monastic community. Morning visits—between 6:00 and 8:00 AM—coincide with the monks' puja ceremony, a deeply moving soundtrack of drums, conch shells, and chanting that resonates across the hillside.</p><ul><li>Established 1960 by Nyeshang community from Manang; Kagyu school Tibetan Buddhism</li><li>Houses ~50 monks with daily puja at dawn and late afternoon</li><li>Three large gilded statues: Shakyamuni, Padmasambhava, and the 16th Karmapa</li><li>Walls covered in detailed thangka paintings and Buddhist cosmological murals</li><li>Hilltop views of Machapuchare, Annapurna South, and the Pokhara Valley</li><li>Best visited at dawn (06:00–08:00) to witness the monks' morning puja ceremony</li></ul>`,
